2026-04-21 01:32:58 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power-supply-to-control-module cable pair (both conductors)'] hypothesis_explanation='At the power-supply module input, a correct 12 V source is present, but the measurement at the control-module input shows that the conductor currently treated as the "+" is at about −12 V with respect to ground while the other is at 0 V. This indicates that the two unmarked cables between the power supply module and the control module are connected with reversed polarity. \n\nBecause of this:\n- The power-supply indicator LED, which is wired for correct polarity across the source, remains off.\n- The control-module inverted-cables indicator LED (red) is forward-biased and thus lights, matching the symptom.\n- The load module sees reversed polarity at its input, so its series diode blocks current and the main lamp does not turn on when the switch is operated.\n\nThe root cause is therefore a polarity inversion (miswiring) of the cable pair linking the power supply module to the control module. The repair is to disconnect this pair at one end and swap the two conductors so that the 12 V and 0 V lines are correctly oriented.'
