2026-04-21 01:33:36 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control input cable (+) internal connection / node labeling', 'Inverted‑cables indicator LED orientation/wiring'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show that at the control‑module input the conductor designated as “+” sits at approximately −12 V with respect to ground, while the conductor designated as “−” is at 0 V. Visual inspection reports that the PSU (+) output is connected to the control input conductor marked (+), and PSU (−) goes to the conductor marked (−); likewise, from the control module forward to the load, the intended + and 0 V paths are wired consistently with the design, and no external polarity inversion is present.\n\nThus, the only way to reconcile: (a) correct 12 V at the PSU input, (b) no green LED on the PSU, (c) the control‑module red LED lit (which should indicate that the 12 V and 0 V lines into the control module are reversed), and (d) the measurement that the control “+” input is at −12 V, is that the internal designation of the control‑module input conductors is itself reversed or miswired. In other words, the conductor that is physically wired to the inverted‑cables detector and through‑line as the intended +12 V node is actually the external terminal currently labeled/assumed as (−), and vice versa.\n\nThis can be implemented either by the internal control‑module input leads being swapped (the conductor marked internally as "+" is connected to the 0 V rail and the one marked as "−" to the +12 V rail), or by the inverted‑cables indicator LED/resistor network being wired to the wrong node (its anode tied to the true 0 V path and cathode toward the true +12 V path). In both cases, with otherwise correct module‑to‑module cabling, the red LED will light even though the inter‑module cabling is correct, and the intended +12 V cannot reach the load in the correct polarity, leaving the lamp off.\n\nTherefore I hypothesize a wiring/labeling fault inside the control module at its input node(s)—effectively a swapped internal connection or misoriented indicator circuit—rather than any fault in the external cables or in the load module.'
